article.headline: Nevada 58, Georgia 47
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Nick Fazekas scored 16 points as Nevada took advantage of its edge in experience and Georgia's poor shooting to beat the Bulldogs 58-47 Friday night. Georgia (0-2) is starting three freshmen and two sophomores and leaning on more underclassmen off its bench. The young Bulldogs scored only two points in the first eight minutes and shot only 17.1 percent from the field in the first half. Georgia's only lead was 2-0. The 6-foot-11 Fazekas, who averaged 27 points in the first two games for Nevada (3-0), blocked four shots. Kevinn Pinkney, a 6-foot-10 senior, added 13 points as the Wolf Pack attacked Georgia freshman center Dave Bliss and sophomore forward Steve Newman inside. A three-point play by one of Georgia's freshman starters, Sundiata Gaines, pulled the Bulldogs to within seven points at 43-36 with 5:24 left to play, but baskets by Pinkney and Fazekas pushed Nevada's lead back to double figures. Gaines led Georgia with 17 points. No other Georgia player scored in double figures. Nevada's 2003-04 season ended with a loss to Georgia Tech in the NCAA tournament's Sweet 16, and the Wolf Pack took a 76-55 win over Georgia State in the Jim Thorpe Classic in Reno, Nev., Sunday. Georgia's bench players were 0-for-9 in the first half and Gaines was 0-for-7. Held scoreless the final 5:52 of the first half, Georgia's drought stretched to 9:22 before Channing Toney scored with 16:29 left in the second half. Nevada, consistently running past Georgia for fast-break baskets, raced to a 13-2 lead. Despite their shooting woes, the Bulldogs found ways to keep the game close. A 3-pointer by Newman at the 5:52 mark of the first half pulled Georgia to within four points at 23-19 before the Wolf Pack led 29-19 at halftime. After the long scoring drought gave Nevada a 14-point lead at 33-19, Georgia answered with an 11-2 run to pull to within five points at 35-30. Georgia coach Dennis Felton attempted to use Corey Gibbs, who missed last season with a knee injury, as a top reserve at forward. Gibbs could not practice on a full-time basis in the preseason as he continued to recover from the injury, and his rust showed when he committed turnovers on three straight possessions midway through the second half. For the game, Georgia made 27.6 percent of its shots from the field. Freshman guard Ramon Sessions added 10 points for Nevada, which plays at Kansas Monday.
